Creating a data-driven, templated, and metaprogramming event system in C++ can be achieved using C++ templates and inheritance. In the following example, I've created a simple event system with a focus on compile-time type checking and automatically generated event IDs.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <typeindex>

class EventData
{
public:
    virtual ~EventData() = default;
};

template <typename T>
class Event : public EventData
{
public:
    T data;

    explicit Event(const T& data)
        : data{data} {}
};

class EventBus
{
public:
    template <typename T>
    void Subscribe(std::function<void(const T&)> callback)
    {
        auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        m_listeners[eventType].push_back([callback](const EventData *eventData) {
            const auto &event = static_cast<const Event<T> *>(eventData);
            callback(event->data);
        });
    }

    template <typename T>
    void Publish(const T &data)
    {
        const auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        if (m_listeners.find(eventType) == m_listeners.end())
        {
            return;
        }

        const auto &listeners = m_listeners[eventType];
        for (const auto &listener : listeners)
        {
            listener(&Event<T>(data));
        }
    }

private:
    std::unordered_map<std::type_index, std::vector<std::function<void(const EventData *)>>> m_listeners;
};

int main()
{
    EventBus eventBus;

    eventBus.Subscribe<int>([](const int &data) {
        std::cout << "Received int event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    eventBus.Subscribe<float>([](const float &data) {
        std::cout << "Received float event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    eventBus.Publish<int>(42);
    eventBus.Publish<float>(3.14f);

    return 0;
}
```

This example demonstrates registering listeners to receive specific event types and publishing events with specific data. The event data types are defined using template specialization, which allows static type checking at compile time. The EventBus class can handle and properly deliver events of any types that inherit from EventData.

Certainly! We can create a callback-based event system without the pub/sub model. Here's an example of an event system using templates and inheritance with direct event dispatching via registered callbacks.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <typeindex>

class EventData
{
public:
    virtual ~EventData() = default;
};

template <typename T>
class Event : public EventData
{
public:
    T data;

    explicit Event(const T& data)
        : data{data} {}
};

class EventDispatcher
{
public:
    template <typename T>
    void Register(const std::function<void(const T&)>& callback)
    {
        auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        m_callbacks[eventType] = [callback](const EventData* eventData) {
            const auto& event = static_cast<const Event<T>*>(eventData);
            callback(event->data);
        };
    }

    template <typename T>
    void Dispatch(const T& data) const
    {
        const auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        if (m_callbacks.find(eventType) == m_callbacks.end())
        {
            return;
        }

        m_callbacks.at(eventType)(&Event<T>(data));
    }

private:
    std::unordered_map<std::type_index, std::function<void(const EventData*)>> m_callbacks;
};

int main()
{
    EventDispatcher eventDispatcher;

    eventDispatcher.Register<int>([](const int& data) {
        std::cout << "Received int event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    eventDispatcher.Register<float>([](const float& data) {
        std::cout << "Received float event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    eventDispatcher.Dispatch<int>(42);
    eventDispatcher.Dispatch<float>(3.14f);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the EventDispatcher class is responsible for handling registered callbacks for specific events. Instead of the pub/sub model, the `Dispatch` function is used to invoke the registered callback directly when an event of a specific type is submitted to EventDispatcher.

In this example, I will implement a data-driven Observer Pattern event system (named ObserverEventBus) and a data-driven Message Queue event system (named MessageQueueEventBus) using modern template and metaprogramming techniques in the context of an Entity Component System. Both systems can be used together to provide versatile event handling.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <typeindex>
#include <queue>

class EventData
{
public:
    virtual ~EventData() = default;
};

template <typename T>
class Event : public EventData
{
public:
    T data;

    explicit Event(const T& data)
        : data{data} {}
};

class ObserverEventBus
{
public:
    template <typename T>
    void Subscribe(std::function<void(const T&)> callback)
    {
        auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        m_listeners[eventType].push_back([callback](const EventData *eventData) {
            const auto &event = static_cast<const Event<T> *>(eventData);
            callback(event->data);
        });
    }

    template <typename T>
    void Publish(const T &data)
    {
        const auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        if (m_listeners.find(eventType) == m_listeners.end())
        {
            return;
        }

        const auto &listeners = m_listeners[eventType];
        for (const auto &listener : listeners)
        {
            listener(&Event<T>(data));
        }
    }

private:
    std::unordered_map<std::type_index, std::vector<std::function<void(const EventData *)>>> m_listeners;
};

class MessageQueueEventBus
{
public:
    template <typename T>
    void Subscribe(std::function<void(const T&)> callback)
    {
        auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        m_listeners[eventType] = [callback](const EventData *eventData) {
            const auto &event = static_cast<const Event<T> *>(eventData);
            callback(event->data);
        };
    }

    template <typename T>
    void EnqueueMessage(const T &data)
    {
        const auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(Event<T>));
        m_messageQueue.push(&Event<T>(data));
    }

    void ProcessMessages()
    {
        while (!m_messageQueue.empty())
        {
            const EventData *eventData = m_messageQueue.front();
            m_messageQueue.pop();

            const auto eventType = std::type_index(typeid(*eventData));
            if (m_listeners.find(eventType) == m_listeners.end())
            {
                continue;
            }

            m_listeners[eventType](eventData);
        }
    }

private:
    std::unordered_map<std::type_index, std::function<void(const EventData *)>> m_listeners;
    std::queue<const EventData *> m_messageQueue;
};

int main()
{
    ObserverEventBus observerEventBus;
    MessageQueueEventBus messageQueueEventBus;

    observerEventBus.Subscribe<int>([](const int &data) {
        std::cout << "ObserverEventBus received int event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    observerEventBus.Subscribe<float>([](const float &data) {
        std::cout << "ObserverEventBus received float event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    observerEventBus.Publish<int>(42);
    observerEventBus.Publish<float>(3.14f);

    messageQueueEventBus.Subscribe<int>([](const int &data) {
        std::cout << "MessageQueueEventBus received int event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    messageQueueEventBus.Subscribe<float>([](const float &data) {
        std::cout << "MessageQueueEventBus received float event, data: " << data << std::endl;
    });

    messageQueueEventBus.EnqueueMessage<int>(101);
    messageQueueEventBus.EnqueueMessage<float>(2.71f);

    messageQueueEventBus.ProcessMessages();

    return 0;
}
```

This implementation provides both the ObserverEventBus and the MessageQueueEventBus in the context of an Entity Component System (ECS). The ObserverEventBus allows systems and components to subscribe and publish events in real-time, while the MessageQueueEventBus offers asynchronous event processing through a message queue.

In this example, both event systems can be used concurrently, enabling flexible event handling in the ECS.

To resolve the problem of forgetting to subscribe or publish events, you can create a more structured approach to event handling in your systems by adopting the following practices:

1. **Interface enforcement**: Create an interface specifically for systems that require event handling. This interface will enforce methods such as `SubscribeEvents()` and `PublishEvents()`. When a new system is created, implement this interface to ensure that the event subscription and publication are set up.

```cpp
class IEventHandlingSystem
{
public:
    virtual ~IEventHandlingSystem() = default;
    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ObserverEventBus& eventBus, MessageQueueEventBus& messageQueueEventBus) = 0;
    virtual void PublishEvents(ObserverEventBus& eventBus, MessageQueueEventBus& messageQueueEventBus) = 0;
};
```

2. **Centralized event system registration**: When adding new systems in the ECS, centralize the registration of event subscriptions and publication in one place. This will ensure you don't forget to set up the event handling whenever a new system is added.

```cpp
class ECS
{
public:
    void RegisterEventHandlingSystem(IEventHandlingSystem* eventHandlingSystem)
    {
        eventHandlingSystem->SubscribeEvents(m_observerEventBus, m_messageQueueEventBus);
        m_eventHandlingSystems.push_back(eventHandlingSystem);
    }

    void PublishEvents()
    {
        for (auto& eventHandlingSystem : m_eventHandlingSystems)
        {
            eventHandlingSystem->PublishEvents(m_observerEventBus, m_messageQueueEventBus);
        }
    }

private:
    ObserverEventBus m_observerEventBus;
    MessageQueueEventBus m_messageQueueEventBus;
    std::vector<IEventHandlingSystem*> m_eventHandlingSystems;
};
```

3. **Code reviews and documentation**: Encourage a culture of code reviews and documentation when implementing new systems. This will provide an opportunity to catch potential issues like missing event subscriptions or publications.

By using interface enforcement and centralized event system registration, you create a more structured approach to event handling and reduce the chances of forgetting to subscribe or publish events for a given system. It will also lead to better maintainability and easier debugging.

