My previous response incorporated the ObserverEventBus in the ECS implementation, but it still requires individual systems to manually subscribe to events. To centralize the event system registration, you can create a base class for systems that need event handling and integrate it with the ECS class.

Here is an example of centralizing event system registration:

1. Create a base class for systems that need event handling:

```cpp
class IEventHandlingSystem
{
public:
    virtual ~IEventHandlingSystem() = default;
    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ECS& ecs) = 0;
};
```

2. Update the `System` class to publicly inherit from `IEventHandlingSystem`:

```cpp
template <class ... Cs>
class System : public SystemBase, public IEventHandlingSystem
{
    // ... other methods and variables

    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ECS& ecs) override { }
};
```

3. Override the `SubscribeEvents` method for systems that need to handle events, subscribing to events using the `ECS` object passed as a parameter:

```cpp
class SystemExample : public System<ComponentA, ComponentB>
{
public:
    SystemExample(ECS& ecs)
        : System(ecs)
    {
    }

    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ECS& ecs) override
    {
        ecs.SubscribeToEvent<int>([](const std::uint32_t elapsedTime, const int& data) {
            std::cout << "SystemExample received int event, data: " << data << ", elapsed time: " << elapsedTime << std::endl;
        });
    }

    // ... other methods
};
```

4. Update the `ECS` class to register event handling systems once and call their `SubscribeEvents` method:

```cpp
class ECS
{
public:
    // ... other methods and variables

    void RegisterEventHandlingSystem(IEventHandlingSystem* system)
    {
        system->SubscribeEvents(*this);
    }
};
```

5. Finally, register systems with event handling in the `ECS` class:

```cpp
ecs.RegisterEventHandlingSystem(new SystemExample(ecs));
```

This approach effectively centralizes event system registration for all event handling systems in your ECS. The `SubscribeEvents` method will be called when the system is created, ensuring the required event subscriptions are set up for each system.

Inheriting from `IEventHandlingSystem` in the `System` class might not be the best approach if you want to promote separation of concerns and make your code more maintainable. Inheriting from `IEventHandlingSystem` will make all systems be event-driven by default, and this might not always be necessary.

Instead, you can create a separate template class that inherits from both `System` and `IEventHandlingSystem`. By doing this, you only make specific systems event-driven when required.

Here's an example of creating a separate event-driven system class:

```cpp
template <class... Cs>
class EventDrivenSystem : public System<Cs...>, public IEventHandlingSystem
{
public:
    EventDrivenSystem(ECS& ecs)
        : System<Cs...>(ecs)
    {
    }

    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ECS& ecs) override {}
};
```

Now you can inherit from `EventDrivenSystem` when creating event-driven systems:

```cpp
class SystemExample : public EventDrivenSystem<ComponentA, ComponentB>
{
public:
    SystemExample(ECS& ecs)
        : EventDrivenSystem(ecs)
    {
    }

    virtual void SubscribeEvents(ECS& ecs) override
    {
        ecs.SubscribeToEvent<int>([](const std::uint32_t elapsedTime, const int& data) {
            std::cout << "SystemExample received int event, data: " << data << ", elapsed time: " << elapsedTime << std::endl;
        });
    }

    // ... other methods
};
```

This approach separates event-driven functionality from the core system class, making it easier to manage and maintain your code. Whenever you need a system to be event-driven, just inherit from `EventDrivenSystem` instead of `System`.

Both approaches (inheriting directly from `IEventHandlingSystem` in the `System` class or creating a separate `EventDrivenSystem` class) have their pros and cons. The former is simpler and more concise, but the latter encourages separation of concerns and can lead to more maintainable code. Your choice depends on your specific use case and project requirements.
